{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565986"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:35:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:35:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18697"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18697"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.33,0.37,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76874"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11429"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62379"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"8926"},{"type":"tags","id":"8993"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30661"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76874"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of recurrent epistaxis, nasal crusting, and rhinorrhoea. He works as an electroplater and has been in this role for two years. He has seasonal allergic rhinitis but no other medical history and takes no regular medications. He has never smoked. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 118/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Nasal examination reveals crusting, erythema of the mucosa, and a small anterior septal perforation. His symptoms have not improved despite a trial of intranasal corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nasal cauterisation","Surgical repair of septal perforation","Removal from exposure","Oral antihistamines","Referral for allergy testing"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with chromium-induced nasal injury, a well-documented occupational hazard in the electroplating industry. The combination of epistaxis, crusting, and septal perforation is characteristic of chromium exposure. The history of allergic rhinitis and failure of intranasal corticosteroids makes this a more challenging diagnostic consideration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoval from exposure\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management. Continued exposure to chromium can lead to progressive damage and larger septal perforations. This may involve temporary reassignment to a different role or strict adherence to appropriate personal protective equipment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasal cauterisation\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially harmful in this case, as the underlying issue is chemical damage to the nasal mucosa rather than a primary bleeding disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical repair of septal perforation\u003C/strong\u003E should not be considered until the patient is removed from exposure and the tissue damage has stabilised. Surgery in the presence of ongoing chemical exposure would likely fail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E might seem reasonable given his history of allergic rhinitis, but would not address the underlying cause of tissue damage from chromium exposure. The failure of intranasal corticosteroids and the presence of septal perforation suggest this is not primarily an allergic condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for allergy testing\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful as this is a direct toxic effect of chromium on the nasal mucosa rather than an allergic response, despite his history of seasonal allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention is crucial in chromium-related occupational injury. This includes proper ventilation systems, appropriate personal protective equipment, regular workplace monitoring, and worker education about the risks of exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chromium exposure in electroplating can cause nasal septum perforation and chronic rhinitis.","Early symptoms of chromium toxicity include epistaxis, nasal irritation, and crusting.","Regular workplace monitoring and personal protective equipment are essential in preventing chromium-related upper airway injury."],"references":["Aiyer RG, Gaurav Kumar. Nasal septal perforations - An occupational hazard in chrome platers. Indian J Physiol Pharmacol. 2011;55(4):311-314.","Sundaram S, Soni S, Soni S, et al. Nasal manifestations in chromium industry workers. Indian J Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2012;64(1):1-4."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62379"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18697"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62379"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T15:27:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T15:29:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11429"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76874"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updat